    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-24T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-24T19:00:00-05:00" n="958"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d958">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/16694: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-24T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 24, 1941—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>350. Your 842, June 19, 1 p.m.<note n="41" xml:id="d958fn1">Not printed, but see
                        telegram No. 851, June 19, 9 p.m., <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_717">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 717</ref>.</note> If suitable occasion
                    arises the Department desires that the Minister for Foreign Affairs be informed
                    that the American naval vessel at Chungking is there in the service of the
                    United States, that it has full right and ample reason for being there, that it
                    is of special service to the American Embassy, and that your Government has no
                    intention of removing it. Incidentally, it is in a place declared by responsible
                    Japanese authorities immune from bombings. The Department must, therefore,
                    reiterate the expectation set forth in its telegram 271 of July 16, 1940, 6
                        p.m.,<note n="42" xml:id="d958fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1940v04#pg_890">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1940, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 890</ref>.</note> that the Japanese
                    Government will issue sufficiently strict and effective instructions <pb
                        facs="0891" n="881" xml:id="pg_881"/> to insure that the Embassy office and
                    the vessel may not again be endangered by Japanese aerial operations.<note
                        n="43" xml:id="d958fn3">For Ambassador Grew’s oral statement on July 8 to
                        Mr. Matsuoka, see <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_718">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 718</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to Tokyo via Shanghai. Repeated to Chungking and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
